        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2107958682" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8941236014946466578">I love Arthurian books and will read most any one that I come in contact with out of curiosity if nothing more. This one sounded interesting so I picked it up at the library and took it home. Very quickly I was pretty horrified by what I found. This book to me read like it was geared to younger readers, the kids who read all the Harry Potter books before they were ten, or the Percy Jackson books or fans of the show <i> Merlin, </i> (which is a great show by the way, if you don&apos;t know what it is do your</span>
  <span id="freeText8941236014946466578" style="display:none">I love Arthurian books and will read most any one that I come in contact with out of curiosity if nothing more. This one sounded interesting so I picked it up at the library and took it home. Very quickly I was pretty horrified by what I found. This book to me read like it was geared to younger readers, the kids who read all the Harry Potter books before they were ten, or the Percy Jackson books or fans of the show <i> Merlin, </i> (which is a great show by the way, if you don't know what it is do yourself a favor and look it up.) That said, I was appalled that the older brother of the main character unconscionably discards any and all females who enter into his life after he grows tired of them. I was shocked that a book for younger readers shows a character who doesn't care about consent and doesn't make this a big deal!? Kids should not be reading this and thinking it is okay to disrespect someone or treat them like garbage. The story is also really unoriginal to boot. So in all honesty, give this book a pass.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8941236014946466578" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
