<span id="freeTextContainer17877046968660319736">Read this one on the train to New York and back. It&apos;s Ok. My knowledge of the Legend of King Arthur was rusty since watching Disney&apos;s The Sword in the Stone about 30 years ago. The chapters are very short and there is a lot of unnecessary dialogue, not to mention I could tell where the story was going 300 pages from the end. There were still scenes that left images in my mind, and that&apos;s what a good author does, after all. I might read the second and third books in the trilogy. But for my my mon</span>
  <span id="freeText17877046968660319736" style="display:none">Read this one on the train to New York and back. It's Ok. My knowledge of the Legend of King Arthur was rusty since watching Disney's The Sword in the Stone about 30 years ago. The chapters are very short and there is a lot of unnecessary dialogue, not to mention I could tell where the story was going 300 pages from the end. There were still scenes that left images in my mind, and that's what a good author does, after all. I might read the second and third books in the trilogy. But for my my money I liked the Crispin trilogy more, when comparing Medieval historical fiction books.</span>
