<div id="review_2779058729" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2779058729" />
    <a title="CarolineFromConcord" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1977854-carolinefromconcord"><img alt="CarolineFromConcord" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1383424713p2/1977854.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2779058729?book_show_action=true">Apr 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="CarolineFromConcord" class="user" itemprop="url" name="CarolineFromConcord" href="/user/show/1977854-carolinefromconcord">CarolineFromConcord</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2779058729" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1976976468741773221">I enjoyed this tale of 12th Century Britain and the ongoing power of Arthurian legends -- until I reached the end. The ending did not work for me. I know it&apos;s a trilogy and you&apos;re supposed to go on and read the other two books, but I prefer trilogy authors who ensure that each book stands alone (Philip Pullman, JRR Tolkein). The novel is very good on historical details, and the obsidian stone that gradually reveals to Arthur his parallel 5th Century life is effective, but I have no interest in f</span>
  <span id="freeText1976976468741773221" style="display:none">I enjoyed this tale of 12th Century Britain and the ongoing power of Arthurian legends -- until I reached the end. The ending did not work for me. I know it's a trilogy and you're supposed to go on and read the other two books, but I prefer trilogy authors who ensure that each book stands alone (Philip Pullman, JRR Tolkein). The novel is very good on historical details, and the obsidian stone that gradually reveals to Arthur his parallel 5th Century life is effective, but I have no interest in following him off to the crusades with so many story lines still up in the air.<br /><br />I also question what age person this book is really for. There are adult themes and instances of violence that would not be right for the children I originally thought would like it.<br /><br />I will say it kept me engaged up to the end, but now I am disappointed.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1976976468741773221" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


