<div id="review_1123102034" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1123102034" />
    <a title="Nukman Salimin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/37605380-nukman-salimin"><img alt="Nukman Salimin" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1123102034?book_show_action=true">Dec 04, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nukman Salimin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nukman Salimin" href="/user/show/37605380-nukman-salimin">Nukman Salimin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1123102034" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14425427738987473812">I personally like books set in the past, so when I saw the cover and read the blurb at the back, I knew this book would be interesting and full of unexpected things going to happen along the way.<br/><br/>When I read the first 30 chapters, I didn&apos;t know where this was going. First there was the bullfight, then about three jumpers who broke into the manor, then a seeing stone. I don&apos;t know how all these related with each other.<br/><br/>Throughout the book, I realized that the book was written in a journal format, b</span>
  <span id="freeText14425427738987473812" style="display:none">I personally like books set in the past, so when I saw the cover and read the blurb at the back, I knew this book would be interesting and full of unexpected things going to happen along the way.<br /><br />When I read the first 30 chapters, I didn't know where this was going. First there was the bullfight, then about three jumpers who broke into the manor, then a seeing stone. I don't know how all these related with each other.<br /><br />Throughout the book, I realized that the book was written in a journal format, by how short the chapters are. This also made my previous point clearer. But the seeing stone made it more complicated. I don't know how the seeing stone relates with Arthur in real life. I kept on reading the chapter where Merlin gives his stone, with all reasons why Merlin gave it to Arthur. I felt like I 'gave up' on the book. But something from the book is pulling me to read more, so I did.<br /><br />When Arthur-in-the-stone came in, things started to get more clearer. I think that the reasons Merlin gave to Arthur will be clearer and answered within the next chapters. It made me want to read, expect, and ask myself questions more.<br /><br />The end was probably one of the best endings I've ever read. Kevin Crossley Holland was smart on his decision. I thought that the two stories in the book were going to meet, but they were parallel. However, their life was somehow related. I loved the twists in the story, how the tension rised and dropped. And I'm so happy that it's not finished. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14425427738987473812" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


